Flight from Moscow
The collapse of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the chance to turn toward democracy, the market economy, and the rule of law.
Some of these countries decisively broke away from their communist past; others were less successful, and a few have catastrophically failed.
Moldova and Georgia belonged until recently to the latter category.
Their economic and political failure was largely due to – actively supported by Russia – secessionist movements that sought to keep both countries within the "sphere of influence" of the Kremlin.
As bloody conflicts erupted in Transnistria, Abkhazia, and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence there into "peacekeeping troops" to maintain control.
For a long time, it was feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly turn hot.
Not only has this not happened, but we can now speak of solutions – because both Georgia and Moldova have begun to achieve a breakthrough toward a market economy and democracy.
This has also been contributed to by the European Union's "neighbourhood policy".
The starting point of these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
Already dangerously close to failure, Georgia has now turned towards the West.
The success of the various "color revolutions" in former Soviet bloc countries also triggered change in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms aimed at bringing the country closer to the EU.
These changes have triggered new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova to restore the territorial integrity of these countries in a peaceful manner.
The experience of Estonia suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policies towards Russia.
When Estonia became independent in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as a country with severe economic problems that was unsuitable for investment.
Estonia was indeed poor, and its main export products were scrap metal and wood, yet its economy grew.
In northeastern Estonia, with its predominantly Russian-speaking population that had settled here during the Soviet era, Russia supported so-called "autonomy movements."
When Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and cut off gas supplies.
High taxes were imposed on the few Estonian products that were allowed to be imported into Russia, and Russia even threatened military intervention.
But Estonia kept its nerve.
The Russian sanctions even helped the country realign its economy toward the West.
Western Europe, on the other hand, did what it could to integrate the Baltic states – Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia – and at the same time sought to avoid conflict with Russia.
In 1994, a free trade agreement with the EU enabled Estonian products to find new markets, and thus Estonia ultimately became one of the most successful post-communist transition countries and joined the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia became independent in 1991, it was not supported in the same way by Western Europe.
Of course, Georgia appeared as a less attractive partner than the Baltic states; the 1990s were marked by coups, counter-coups, and civil wars, with two regions – Abkhazia and South Ossetia – essentially breaking away with Russian support.
The country has done its best to forget its dismal past.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army has been strengthened, and the country's leadership is young, dynamic, and eager to advance the country.
Thanks to Georgia's flat 12% income tax – probably the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has raised pensions and increased social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a judicial reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and by over 10% in 2006.
Georgia is trying to ease tensions over Abkhazia and South Ossetia; Russia, however, accuses the country of aggression and ethnic cleansing.
Its main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and to prevent reconciliation with the breakaway regions.
The powers that matter in Georgia are Russia and to a certain extent the United States.
Europe must show that it is also important.
Estonia has – at the time of its independence and again during the recent crisis over the relocation of a Soviet-era monument – shown that it is possible to resist Russian pressure with determination and strong support.
Europe must realize that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe enabled Estonia to find new markets, this can be the means by which the Georgians can help themselves.
Georgia has every reason to hope that it will achieve genuine independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is more threatened by Russia than the Estonians or even the Georgians ever were?
The lack of reform successes is partly the result of secessionist movements supported by Russia.
The fact that the industrialized region of Transnistria – whose Russian- and Ukrainian-speaking population feared that the majority of Moldovans, who are of Romanian descent, planned closer ties with Romania – seceded from Moldova dealt a severe blow to the country's independence right from the beginning.
It was followed by a civil war, and in 1992 Russian troops marched into Transnistria, where they still are today.
The independence of Transnistria was never recognized – neither by Moldova nor internationally.
It is said that lawlessness and corruption prevail there.
Moldova is highly indebted, unemployment is high, and its once prestigious wine industry is in decline.
Russia occasionally cuts off gas supplies, and many of the four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Government representatives of Moldova have made four fruitless visits to Moscow to try to convince President Vladimir Putin to seek a solution and withdraw Russian troops.
A desperate Voronin has asked the EU observer mission Eubam for help, but an EU initiative would require Russian cooperation.
Unfortunately, the West seems to lack current insights into the situation in Moldova.
For example, in April, the EU and also the USA learned only through a leaked report in Germany about a proposed peace agreement.
This, it seems, would favor Russia, as Moldova would recognize Transnistria as a legitimate unit within it.
If Russia has thus outmaneuvered the West, this would be a dangerous precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
